## 4. New: Remote Ad Control Configuration

The generator **does not** hardcode any ad images. Instead, every generated page includes JavaScript that fetches a live JSON configuration from a URL defined in `site-config.json` (or a default path). This JSON controls:

- Which ads are shown on which page (depot, blog, or global).
- For each ad slot (top, middle, footer) per page:
  - `enabled` (true/false)
  - `title` (text to display in the 1/3 column on desktop, above image on mobile)
  - `image_mobile` (URL of image for screens < 768px)
  - `image_desktop` (URL of image for screens ≥ 768px)
  - `link_url` (optional – makes the whole ad clickable)

### 4.1 Location of the Remote JSON

The remote JSON must be accessible via a URL. In `site-config.json`, add:

```json
"ad_config_url": "https://your-cloudflare-worker-or-static-host.com/ads-config.json"
```

If not provided, the JavaScript falls back to `"/assets/ads/config.json"` (so you can host the file inside the same `public/` directory and update it without rebuilding).

### 4.2 Structure of the Remote JSON

```json
{
  "depots": {
    "123": {
      "top_ad": {
        "enabled": true,
        "title": "Special Offer near Pune Depot",
        "image_mobile": "/assets/images/ads/pune-depot-mobile.jpg",
        "image_desktop": "/assets/images/ads/pune-depot-desktop.jpg",
        "link_url": "https://example.com/offer"
      },
      "middle_ad": { "enabled": false },
      "footer_ad": { "enabled": true, "title": "Book Now", "image_mobile": "...", "image_desktop": "..." }
    },
    "456": { ... }
  },
  "blogs": {
    "my-blog-post": {
      "top_ad": { "enabled": true, "title": "Read more", "image_mobile": "...", "image_desktop": "..." }
    }
  },
  "default": {
    "top_ad": { "enabled": true, "title": "Default Ad", "image_mobile": "/assets/images/ads/default-mobile.jpg", "image_desktop": "/assets/images/ads/default-desktop.jpg" },
    "middle_ad": { "enabled": false },
    "footer_ad": { "enabled": true, ... }
  }
}
```

### 4.3 How Pages Use the Remote JSON

- On page load, the JavaScript fetches this JSON (with cache‑busting via `?t=Date.now()` or a short TTL).
- It determines the current page type:
  - Depot page: extracts depot ID from the URL path (e.g., `/division/district/tehsil/123/index.html` → `123`).
  - Blog page: extracts blog ID from URL (e.g., `/blogs/my-blog.html` → `my-blog`).
  - Other pages (home, bus-schedule, static): use `"default"` or a special key `"global"`.
- For each ad container (`.ad-container.top_ad`, `.middle_ad`, `.footer_ad`), it looks up the corresponding configuration (page‑specific first, then fallback to `default`).
- If `enabled` is `true`, it renders the ad as a **combined title+image block**:
  - Desktop: flex row, title occupies 1/3 width, image occupies 2/3 width.
  - Mobile: flex column, title above image.
  - If `link_url` is provided, the entire block becomes a clickable `<a>` tag.
  - The image uses `srcset` or separate `image_mobile` / `image_desktop` based on `window.innerWidth`.
- If `enabled` is `false`, the ad container is hidden (`display: none`).

### 4.4 Manual Image Uploads Without Rebuilding

Because the generator copies the `assets/img/ads/` folder to `public/assets/images/ads/`, you can later upload new images directly into `public/assets/images/ads/` (via FTP, SCP, or file manager) and update the remote JSON to point to those local paths (e.g., `"/assets/images/ads/new-image.jpg"`). No rebuild is required.

