## 5. Blog Images (Markdown Support)

### 5.1 Directory & Copying

- Place blog images in `assets/img/blogs/` (any filenames, any subfolder structure).
- The generator’s existing `copyImagesToPublic()` method must be extended to **recursively copy** the entire `assets/img/` directory, preserving subfolders. This will copy `blogs/` and `ads/` subfolders to `public/assets/images/blogs/` and `public/assets/images/ads/`.

### 5.2 Markdown Image Syntax

The `processBlogContent()` method must be enhanced to convert standard Markdown image syntax:

`![alt text](image-url)` → `<img src="image-url" alt="alt text" class="blog-image">`

**Important:** The image URL should be relative to the site root, e.g., `/assets/images/blogs/my-photo.jpg`. The generator does **not** modify the URL; it trusts the author to use the correct path.

### 5.3 Example Blog JSON

```json
{
  "id": "pune-trip",
  "title": "A Day in Pune",
  "date": "2025-03-15",
  "content": "We started at Pune depot. ![Pune Bus Stand](/assets/images/blogs/pune-bus.jpg) The journey was amazing."
}
```

### 5.4 CSS for Blog Images

Add to the inline CSS:

```css
.blog-content img {
  max-width: 100%;
  height: auto;
  border-radius: 8px;
  margin: 1rem 0;
  display: block;
}
```

